CONSIGNEE COST TO DISPOSE UNKNOWN.  DISPOSAL PERFORMED BY CLEAN HARBOR. REPORT NO. 90100022 PLEASE BE INFORMED THAT THIS WAS A FAILURE OF THE RECEIVER'S STORAGE TANK. THE TANK WAS INSIDE THEIR BLDG.  THEY FACILITATED AND INCURRED THE COST OF THE CLEAN-UP.  WE SUBMIT AN ESTIMATED COST FOR LOSS OF MATERIAL.  PLEASE BE INFORMED THAT THE TANK TAILER USED TO TRANSPORT THIS MATERIAL DID NOT FAIL.

column168: OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 5000 GALLONS OF GLYCOL ETHER EM FOR DELIVERY TO PHILLIPS 66 COMPANY IN COMMERCE CITY, COLO. WITH A STOP-OFF AT THERE PLANT SITE IN LA JUNTA, COLO FOR THE OFF LOADING OF 1000 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT INTO THERE STORAGE TANK.  THIS APPEARED TO BE A NEW INSTALLATION AS THERE WAS STILL PAINT ON THE SITE GLASS GAUGE.  OUR DRIVER WAS OPERATING HIS TRACTOR PUMP, AND THE COMPANY OPERATOR WAS TO TELL OUR DRIVER WHEN THE STORAGE TANK WAS FULL AND WE WOULD SHUT DOWN THE PUMPING.  THE SITE GLASS HAD A READING OF 0 TO 48 INCHES, AND THE SHIFT FOREMAN HAD TOLD HIS OPERATOR TO STOP THE PUMPING WHEN THE GAUGE READ 39 INCHES OF PRODUCT.  THE OPERATOR FAILED TO TELL THE DRIVER WHEN THE PRODUCT REACHED THE 39 INCH MARK, AND BEFORE THE PRODUCT FILLED THE TANK, THE MANHOLE DOME LID ON THE STORAGE TANK STARTED LEAKING PRODUCT DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK, WITH AN ESTIMATED SPILL OF FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT THE MANHOLE COVER HAD NEVER BEEN TIGHTENED DOWN AND THIS ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE THE TANK.  THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY THE COMPANY OPERATOR AND PUT INTO WASTE CONTAINERS PROVIDED.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS OF CHROME WATER [RQ, HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID, NOS (CHROMIUM), ORME-E, NA 9189, (D007)] WAS SPILLED INTO THE CONTAINED LOADING AREA AT THE BOEING RENTON FACILITY BLDG. NO 483 DUE TO AN INADVERTENT OVERFILLING OF THE VACUUM TANKER. THE LEVEL/VOLUME GAUGE ON THE TANKER INDICTED ONLY 86% OF THE 5,000 GALLON CAPACITY HAD BEEN LOADED WHEN MATERIAL BEGAN TO FLOW FROM THE SCRUBBER VENT PIPE OF THE VACUUM MOTOR.  THIS VACUUM TANKER IS EQUIPPED WITH AN OVERFLOW PREVENTER VALVE ON THE VACUUM UNIT TO PREVENT A DISCHARGE FROM THE VENT SHOULD AN OVERFILL OCCUR.  THE PREVENTER VALVE FAILED TO WORK AS DESIGNED. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE PART OF THE MATERIAL WAS UNLOADED, THE SPILLED MATERIAL COLLECTED, AND THE VEHICLE HOSES AND OTHER EQUIPMENT WERE WASHED DOWN. THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE CONSIGNEE AND UNLOADED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. SUBSEQUENT EXAMINATION OF THE TANKER INDICATED THAT THE BOTH THE GAUGE AND THE OVERFLOW PREVENTER HAD FAILED.  BOTH HAVE NOW BEEN REPAIRED.

column168: ON 9/20/90, TANK CAR GATX 22527, CONTAINING WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS (XYLENE/TOLUENE MIXTURE), WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY YARD PERSONNEL IN THE FLINT, MICHIGAN RAIL YARD LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY ONLY WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO AWAIT REPAIRS.  THE DETROIT BIDS TERMINAL MANAGER AND A FOREMAN RESPONSED AND REPAIRED THE CAR ON 9/21/90 BY REPLACING A WORN MANWAY COVER GASKET.  THE BIDS TERMINAL IN DETROIT LOADED THE CAR FOR PETRO CHEM PROCESSING.

TRAILER ICSU 358599 ARRIVED CSXT AUGUSTA YARD ON FLAT CAR WICT 902469. TRAILER WAS NOT LEAKING BUT ENGINEER MAY COMPLAINED OF FOUL ODOR. INSPECTION REVEALED LOAD HAD SHIFTED 12" TOWARD DOORS, BUT NO LIQUID ON FLOOR INSIDE TRAILER.  SHIPMENT WAS ALLOWED TO MOVE TO DESTINATION, WHERE CONSIGNEE OFFLOADED, INSPECTED SHIPMENT AND DETERMINED A SINGLE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AT BOTTOM BY A NAIL IN THE LOADING PALLET. column168: FOUND ONE CARTON CONTAINING 4-1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES LEAKING.  CARTON WAS OPENED AND FOUND CAPS ON BOTTLES WERE LOOSE.  CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND WIPED OFF BOTTLES.  BOTTLES PUT BACK INTO CARTON AND WRAPPED THE CARTON WITH PLASTIC.  THE CARTON ABSORBED THE LEAKAGE, SO NO LEAKAGE WAS ON FLOOR OF TRAILER TO CLEAN UP.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT UNLOAD SITE WITH LOAD OF 89OCTANE NOLEAD GASOLINE FOR CUSTOMERS ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  DRIVER OFFLOADED INTO TANK MARKED NOLEAD +, AS IT TURNED OUT CUSTOMER HAD INCORRECT AND NON COMPLIANT MARKINGS AND COLOR CODES ON PRODUCT UNLOAD LINES/VALVES AND STORAGE TANK. (CUSTOMER HAD ATTACHED A PAPER TAG TO BACK SIDE OF UNLOAD VALVE/LINE STATING LOAD WAS TO GO INTO SPECIFIED TANK, WHICH WAS ANOTHER TANK AT SITE-OUR DRIVER HOOKED UP TO WHAT HE THOUGHT (COLOR CODES SAID IT WAS) WAS THE CORRECT TANK AND STARTED TO PUMP OFF THE LOAD INTO STORAGE TANK.  THE TANK WAS THE INCORRECT TANK, IT FILLED UP AND OVERFILLED WOTH THE SPILLAGE OF APPROX. 5700 GALLONS ONTO THE DYKE AREA AROUND STORAGE TANKS.  THE DYKE DID NOT RETAIN THE PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT DID NOT OVERFLOW THE DYKE BUT RATHER PENETRATED THE GROUND UNDER THE DYKE AMD MIGRATED UNDERGROUND TO AREA SURROUNDING THE TANKS; DIKE NOT UP TO CODE AS IT WAS CONSTRUCTED WITH NONPERMEABLE MATERIALS AND THUSLY DID NOT RETAIN LIQUID.  DRIVER CALLED OUR DISPATCH OFFICE AS SOON AS HE NOTICED SPILLAGE, OUR OPERATIONS MGR. WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO SCENE.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AS WELL AS RESPONSE FROM LOCAL POLICE.  EPA WAS NOTIFIED OF SPILL AND RESPONDED AS WELL.  A PROFESSIONAL CLEAN-UP COMPANY WAS CALLED IN TO EFFECT CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP.

column168: PRESSURE BUILT UP IN STORAGE TANK AND BLEW UNLOADING LINE OUT OF TANK.

OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DELIVERING 800 GALS OF MATERIAL TO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE.  AFTER STARTING TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL THE VALVE ON THE CUSTOMER'S FIBERGLAS STORAGE TANK STRATED TO LEAK PRODUCT.  AS OUR DRIVER AND THE RECEIVER WERE SHUTTING DOWN THE VALVE COMPLETELY SEPARATED FROM THE STORAGE TANK AND THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK WERE SPILLED.  THE SPILL CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP WERE HANDLED BY THE CUSTOMER.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION.  WHEN HE STARTED TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED DRIPPING FROM THE BELLY OF HIS TRAILER. BUCKETS WERE PLACED TO CATCH THE BULK OF THE MATERIAL DURING DELIVERY.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND SENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY.  HE PROCEEDED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  AFTER STARTING TO UNLOAD A SLIGHT DRIP WAS NOTICED AT THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  THE DRIVER WAS GOING TO SHUT DOWN AND ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK BUT THE CONSIGNEE PROVIDED A BUCKET TO CATCH THE MATERIAL AND REQUESTED THAT OUR DRIVER PROCEED WITH THE UNLOADING.  OUR DRIVER REPORTED THE FAULTY VALVE ON HIS RETURN TO THE TERMINAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT AROUND 8:AM ON 9-18-90 A THIELE-ENGDAHL EMPLOYEE ARRIVED AT A LOCAL MANUFACTURING PLANT TO PICK UP (2) 500 GALLON TOTES (PORTABLE TANKS) OF SOLVENT BLEND USED AT OUR RICHMOND PLANT.  BY 9:20AM THE TWO TOTES WERE LOADED.  THE TRUCK HEADED BACK TO OUR PLANT.  AS THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT TURN, AN ONCOMING CAR WAS ILLEGALLY PASSED BY ANOTHER CAR ON ITS RIGHT.  THIS FORCED THE TRUCK DRIVER TO CUT THE TURN MORE SHARPLY THAN PLANNED.  THE SHARP TURN CASED THE TOTES TO SHIFT TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE VEHICLE, THEIR MOMENTUM AT THE OUTSIDE OF THE TURN RADIUS CAUSED THE TRUCK TO TIP OVER.  THE TOTE LIDS POPPED OFF, RELEASING SOLVENT.  THE DRIVER ESCAPED FROM THE VEHICLE AND AS HE APPROACHED THE PLANT (500' AWAY), PLANT PERSONNEL NOTIFIED EMERGENCY AUTHORITIES.  PLANT PERSONNEL THEN SHUT OFF THE VEHICLE ENGINE TO PREVENT A SOURCE OF IGNITION, CONSTRUCTED A DIKE AND BEGAN RECOVERING PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM THE TRUCK.  TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE ACCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE, THE PLANT IS DOING THE FOLLOWING: 1) PLANT FREIGHT TRUCKS ARE HAVING A SYSTEM INSTALLED CONSISTING OF AN ADDED RAILING, WITH A NYLON STRAP AND RATCHET TO BETTHER SECURE LOADS. 2) A SAFETY MEETING WAS HELD COVERING DEFENSIVE DRIVING TECHNIQUE AND PROPER FREIGHT PLACEMENT WITHIN TRANSPORT VEHICLES (TOTES AND DRUMS) AND CHECKS TO BE MADE ON CONTAINER STABILIZATION, CLOSURE, LABELING.

DRIVER GOT TO CONSIGNEE AND WAS INSIDE BUILDING DOING PAPERWORK AND MAKING PHONE CALLS BEFORED HE UNLOADED.  LADY AT THE PLANT NOTICED A LITTLE PRODUCT ON TRUCK AND INFORMED DRIVER.  DRIVER CHECKED AND FOUND THE MANHOLE WAS STUCK OPEN A LITTLE AND HE LOST ABOUT A TEACUP.  CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP AND WILL DISPOSE OF CLEANING PRODUCT.

CHEMTREC CALLED ME CONCERNING LTC IN MEMPHIS, TN.  SHIPPER CONTACTED ME AND STATED THAT HE WOULD HAVE CAR FIXED.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER ON 10/01/90. CAR HAD 6 MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE.  THEY WERE SECURED AND CAR WAS RELEASED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: PRODUCT SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF A SINGLE VEHICLE ROLLOVER ACCIDENT.  AS THE CARGO TANK ROLLED OVER, AN UNLOADING PRESSURIZATION FITTING ON THE DOME LID WAS BROKEN BY CONTACT WITH GROUND ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. APPROXIMATELY 4480 LBS. ESCAPED BEFORE THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY A RESPONDING HAZMAT TEAM FROM SOUTH BEND, INDIANA.  REMAINDER OF PRODUCT IN THE DAMAGED CARGO TANK WAS TRANSLOADED BY COMPANY PERSONNEL INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A SMALL AREA DUE TO THE AREA'S NATURAL CONTOUR AND GRADING.  FOLLOWING DISCUSSIONS WITH THE STATE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AUTHORITIES AND THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT, NEUTRALIZATION OF THE SPILL WAS ACCOMPLISHED ON SITE.  NO WASTE WAS PRODUCED THAT REQUIRED OFF-SITE TRANSPORT FOR TREATMENT OR DISPOSAL.

PRODUCT WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM CARGO TANK VIA A TRACTOR-MOUNTED TRANSFER PUMP AND TRANSFER HOSES.  DURING THE UNLOADING, A TRANSFER HOSE RUPTURED. TWENTY GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED BEFORE DRIVER COULD STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT BY CLOSING THE CARGO TANK INTERNAL VALVE.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY PLANT PERSONNEL. column168: ON MONDAY SEPTEMBER 24, 1990, AT 2005 HOURS, YARD ASIGNMENT AR-7 REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 12190 LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR, WHILE IT WAS BEING CLASSIFIED IN THE NORTH YARD. TRAINMAN L M HALL BREATHED SOME OF THE FUMES WHEN THE ACID SPLASHED OUT OF THE SAFETY VENT PIPING AND RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR.  TRAINMAN HALL FELT LIGHT-HEADED AND REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  TRAINMAN HALL WAS TAKEN TO RICHMOND MEMORIAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS CHECKED AND GIVEN OXYGEN, WHICH RELIEVED THE DISCOMFORT.  TRAINMAN HALL WAS RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL AND REPORTED BACK TO WORK AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS. AFTER THE TANK CAR WAS REPORTED LEAKING TO THE YARDMASTER AT 2005 HOURS, IT WAS MOVED TO NO. 20 TRACK IN THE NORTH YARD, WHERE IT WAS ISOLATED UNTIL REPAIR COULD BE MADE.  THE YARDMASTER CONTACTED MR.  T.W. GRUBBS, SUPERVISOR POLICE AND SAFETY, AT 2010 HOURS.  ON HIS ARRIVAL AT ACCA YARD, HE MADE AN INSPECTION OF THE THE TANK CAR AND FOUND IT WAS NOT LEAKING, BUT HAD BEEN LEAKING WHEN IN MOTION FROM AROUND THE AREA OF THE FITTINGS WHICH CONTAINED THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 2130 HOURS AND THEY,IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, CONSERV INCORPORATED OF 676 COUNTY ROAD, NICHOLS, FLORIDA 33863.  AT 2210 HOURS, MR. GILL MULLINO OF CONSERV INC. CALLED AND MR GRUBBS ADVISED HIM OF THE CONDITION OF THE TANK CAR AND AND THE INJURY WHICH HAD RESULTED FROM THE RELEASE.  MR. MULLINO ADVISED THAT HE WOULD INFORM HIS COMPANY OF THE CONDITION OF THE TANK CAR AND HAVE SOMEONE CONTACT MR GRUBBS BY 1000 HOURS ON TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 25, 1990, TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE A REPAIR CREW RESPOND TO ACCA YARD. AT 1030 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 25, 1990, MS. ROBIN SMITH, COORDINATOR, TRANSPORTATION SERVICES FOR CHEMTECH INDUSTRIES INC., 1655 DES PERES ROAD, ST LOUIS, MISSOURI 63131, THE COMPANY WHO OWNS THE CHEMICAL AND LEASES THE TANK CAR, CALLED AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS NOT LEAKING,BUT HAD LEAKED FROM A RUPTURED SAFETY PRESSURE DISC WHEN IN MOTION.  MS SMITH ADVISED THAT SHE WOULD CONTACT A TANK CAR REPAIR COMPANY IN THE RICHMOND VIRGINIA AREA AND HAVE THEM CONTACT MR. GRUBBS TO ADVISE WHEN THEY WOULD ARRIVE TO MAKE REPAIRS.  AT 1440 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 25,1990, MR AL REESMAN OF GENERAL RAILWAY SERVICE ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD.  THE REPAIR CREW MADE AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR AND WHEN THE CLOSURE THAT HOLDS THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC WAS OPENED, THE CREW  FOUND NO SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  A SAFETY PRESSURE DISC WAS PLACED INTO THE CLOSURE AND TIGHTENED DOWN TO SEAL THE CLOSURE.  AFTER COMPLETING THE REPAIRS, AN INSPECTION WAS AGAIN MADE OF THE TANK CAR AND AT THIS TIME, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TANK HEAD ON THE "A" END OF THE TANK CAR APPROXIMATELY TWO FEET DOWN FROM THE TOP ON THE RIGHT SIDE.  A WOODEN PEG WAS PROTRUDING FROM THE HOLE APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES IN LENGTH.  THE HOLE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A HOLE IN THE INNER LINER WHICH ALLOWED THE ACID TO EAT A HOLE THROUGH THE METAL OF THE TANK CAR.  THE GENERAL RAILW

column168: DRIVER PULLED UNIT INTO PETRO TRUCK STOP, SAN ANTONIO, TX TO STOP FOR THE NIGHT.  WHILE INSPECTING HIS TRUCK, THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE SAFETY DEPT. IN JOPLIN.  THE MANIFEST REVEALED THAT THERE WERE 24 DRUMS OF WASTE ZINCEW CYANIDE, POISON 8, UN1713, 31 DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID, N.O.S., ORM-E, NA9189 (NICKEL STRIP SOLUTION), AND 7 BAGS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID, N.O.S., ORM-E, NA9139 (SLIDGE FROM WASTE WATER TREATMENT).  JOPLIN SAFETY NOTIFIED THE TRUCKSTOP MANAGER, SAN ANTONIO FIRE DEPT., TEXAS WATER COMMISSION, AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT NO. 39549).  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC., OF HOUSTON, TX WAS CONTRACTED TO WORK THE LEAKER.  THE LEAK TURNED OUT TO BE COMING FROM A 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM OF WHAT WAS LABELED AND MANIFESTED TO BE WASTE, ZINC CYANIDE, POISON B, UN1713.  FOUR DRUMS HAD BEEN METAL BANDED TOGETHER TO A PALLET.  WHILE IN TRANSIT, THE FLEXING OF THE PLASTIC DRUMS ALLOWED THE METAL BAND TO SLIDE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS.  THIS ALLOWED ONE DRUMS TO FALL FORWARD AND AGAINST ONE OF THE 7 BAGS OF WASTE ON BOARD AT APPROXIMATLEY A 45 DEGREE ANGLE.  THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS WERE EQUIPPED WITH VENT CAPS.  THE VENT CAP ALLOWED ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO COME OUT.THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED, TRAILER FLOOR AND GROUND DECONTAMINATED AND TRUCK WAS ALLOWED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATIN.  WHILE OFFLOADING AT ENCYCLE, CORPUS CHRISTI, TX, A FORKLIFT DRIVER PUNCTURED A DRUM WITH A FORK LIFT TINE ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF WASTE, ZINC CYANIDE, POISON B UN1713, TO SPILL OUT.  THIS WAS CLEANED UP BY ENCYCLE PEOPLE. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY ENCYCLE PEOPLE, THE MATERIAL HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY IDENTIFIED, BOTH BY LABELS AND ON THE MANIFEST, BY THE SHIPPER, SHEPHARD PLATING CO., RACINE, WI.  THE MATERIAL, IN FACT, WAS 50 DRUMS OF WASTE , ZINC CYANIDE, POISON B, UN1713, AND ONE (1) DRUM OF HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID, N.O.S., ORM-E, NA9189 (NICKEL STRIP SOLUTION).

TRANSPORT OPERATOR WILLIE JOINER NOTIFIED ELLENWOOD DISPATCHER, ERIC MARBLE, THAT HE HAS A SUBSTANCE LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  MR JOINER WAS INSTRUCTED TO GO TO OUR BIRMINGHAM, ALABAMA FACILITY FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  MR JOINER DISCOVERED ONE LEAKING FIVE GALLON PAIL OF COMPOUND LIQUID NOS FLAMMABLE LIQUID UN1993.  THE LIQUID HAD LEAKED OUT. THE PAIL WAS REMOVED AT BIRMINGHAM, ALABAMA.  NO PRODUCT WAS LEFT FOR DISPOSAL.  BILLY HILL, THE SUPERVISOR AT BIRMINGHAM, GAVE THIS INFORMATION TO ME OVER THE TELEPHONE AT 0045 ON 9/21/90.

column168: RAILROAD EMPLOYEES REPORTED LEAK FROM RAIL CAR AT 2225 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 8, 1990, WITH A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA IN AIR.  EMPLOYEES WERE ADVISED TO AVOID AREA; SWITCHING OPERATIONS WERE HALTED IN CLOSE PROXIMITY.  RAIL CAR WAS INSPECTED BY UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD DISTRICT SPECIAL AGENT, K.C. DECHANT, WITH VAPOR DISPERSION IN AREA OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING VISIBLE FROM A DISTANCE OF SEVERAL HUNDRED FEET.  DUE TO THE VOLUME OF VAPORS PRESENT, PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND SELF-CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS WERE REQUIRED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION, WITH LIQUID PRODUCT SUBSEQUENTLY FOUND TO EMANATING FROM VALVE STEM AND UNLOADING PORT OF A-END LIQUID VALVE.  VALVE STEM LEAKAGE WAS STOPPED ENTIRELY WITH TIGHTENING OF PACKING SLEEVE; ALSO AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO FURTHER TIGHTEN ANGLE VALVE.  WHILE NO PERCEPTIBLE MOVEMENT OF HAND WHEEL WAS NOTED, TIGHTENING DID DIMINISH LEAK FROM OUTLET.  LEAK WAS COMPLETELY STOPPED WITH TIGHTENING OF PORT PLUG, WHICH HAD BEEN FOUND LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  AT 2355 HOURS, NO LEAKAGE WAS DETECTABLE AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  ALL LEAKAGE WAS VAPORIZED AND DISPERSED.  MR. DECHANT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE OF THIS INCIDENT.  UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, JIM BRUNSON, NOTIFIED TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA.

THE FIRE WAS CONFINED TO THE TOP OF THE CAR AROUND THE MANWAY COVER.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN NOTIFIED. INSPECTIUON BY MR. RODABOUGH DETERMINED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN MISHANDLED WHILE BEING SWITCHED AND THE PHOSPHORUS HAD SPRAYED FROM THE MANWAY COVER ALONG THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CAR WAS MOVED TO A SAFE LOCATION FOR CLEANING. ON 09/25/90 MR. WILLARD LARSON AND MR. STEVE WELCH, FMC PERSONNEL, ASSISTED MR. RODABOUGH IN BURNING OFF THE RESIDUE PHOSPHORUS FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE MANWAY LID WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  AFTER CLEANUP AND REPAIR CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

FREIGHT DAMAGE PREVENTION REPORTED A LEAKING TRAILER AT THE JACKSONVILLE RAMP.  TRAILER HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE WHO UPON INSPECTION REJECTED TRAILER DUE TO THE LOAD HAVING SHIFTED IN TRANSIT. TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO CSX RAMP WHERE IT WAS FOUND LEAKING.  HAZMAT RETAINED HAZARDS ENVIRONMENTAL TO CONDUCT CLEANUP AND CSXT HAZMAT MGR. G L BLANKENSHIP RESPONDED TO RAMP.  FIVE ONE GALLONS JUGS WERE FOUND TO HAVE BURST OPEN AND SPILLED ACID IN THE TRAILER.  THE JUGS WERE OVERPACKED AND THE TRAILER MOVED TO SMALLEY TRANSPORTATION'S TERMINAL TO DECON IT. LEAKAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME.

column168: UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY MR. RUSS VASSER ADVISING CREWS HAD REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR A CUT OF NINE LOADED AMMONIA CARS.  INSPECTION BY MR STINE DETERMINED THAT VAPOR WAS LEAKING FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY NOZZLE PRESSURE PLATE AT THE NOZZLE JOINT BELOW BOTH LIQUID LINES.  INTERNAL TANK PRESSURE WAS 150 PSI. ACCOUNT TANK'S PRESSURE AND THE INACCESSABILITY OF THE STUD NUTS, NO ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO STOP THE LEAK.  MR JOE DEBNAM AT CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFEID AS WAS TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA.  CONTACT WAS ALSO MADE WITH MR JOHN GOEBEL AT FARMLAND INDUSTRIES AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR SECURING A SUITABLE RESIDUE CAR FOR TRANSFER. ON SEPTEMBER 4, 1990 MR. STINE CONDUCTED THE TRANSFER WITH THE HELP OF SPECIAL AGENTS-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C.C. SHUPE, D.A. LOW, AND C.L. HILL AND BOB EWOLDT, AAR INSPECTOR, AND A.D. MATY, SHIEF INSPECTOR AAR BURAEU OF EXPLOSIVES.  USING A CORKEN COMPRESSOR TRANSFER WAS STRATED AT 0835 HOURS AND WAS DONE PUMPING LIQUID PRODUCT AT 1045 HOURS.  STARTED VAPOR DOWN OF LEAKING CAR AT 1110 HOURS AND STOPPED AT 1305 HOURS.  PRESSURE REDUCED FROM 180 PSI TO 85 PSI.  MR. GOEGEL HAD ADVISED THIS WAS SUFFICIENT AS THE CAR WAS GOING TO BE FORWARDED TO THEIR LAWRENCE, KANSAS PLANT FOR COMPLETE VAPOR DOWN PROIR TO BEING SENT TO A SHOP.  CAR STENCILLED "LEAKY TANK DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED", AS REQUIRED.

column168: ON SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 8, 1990, CAR MP 715571 WAS SPOTTED INTO THE FERTILIZER CENTER FARM SUPPLY AT RIRIE, IDAHO.  ON MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 10, 1990, EMPLOYEES OF FERTILIZER CENTER FARM SUPPLY FOUND CAR HAD BEEN LEAKING OVER THE WEEKEND OUT OF THE BOTTOM NORTH END HOPPER.  PRODUCT EAS ON THE TRACK BETWEEN THE RAILS WHERE CAS WAS SPOTTED AND LEAKED OUT UNTIL PRODUCT REACHED THE BOTTOM PART OF THE CAR.  IT IS ESTIMATED BETWEEN 1,500 AND 2,00 POUNDS LEAKED OUT AT THIS LOCATION.  A UPRR MECHANICAL PERSON WAS DISPATCHED TO CHECK CAR AND FOUND HOPPER WAS SEALED INTACT; HOWEVER, THE SLIDE DOOR HAD NOT BEEN CLOSED PROPERLY, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT WHILE EN ROUTE FROM SHIPPER AND WHILE SPOTTED AT THE FERTILIZER CENTER FARM SUPPLY.  THE SLIDE DOR WAS THEN CLOSED PROPERLY AND CAR SENT BACK TO POCATELLO FOR REWEIGHTING.  THE BILL OF LADING SHOWED 199,750 POUNDS IN THE CAR AND 189300 POUNDS WHEN IT WAS REWEIGHED, FOR A LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 10,450 POUNDS.  THE FERTILIZER CENTER FARM SUPPLY SALVAGED WHAT THEY COULD AND THE REST WAS CLEANED UP BY THEM,.  IT APPEARED THIS CAR LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT WHILE EN ROUTE FROM SHIPPER, DUE TO SLIDE DOOR NOT BEING CLOSED ALL THE WAY.

column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS H.W RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY TRAIN MANGEMENT-OMAHA THAT TANK CAR GATX 22806 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING AND WAS PRESENTLY SET OUT AT THE HARER SIDING JUST EAST OF MONTPELIER, IDAHO AT MP 102.3.  INSPECTION BY MR RODABOUGH DETERMINED THAT THE TOP CONTROL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE OUTLET CAP WAS LOOSE.  MR. RODABOUGH SECURED THE OUTLET VALVE.  HE THEN REMOVED THE NOZZLED CAP AND THE EXCESS ALCOHOL WAS RECOVERED AND RETURNED TO THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR.  THE OUTLET NOZZLE WAS THEN TAPED WITH TEFLON AND THE CAP WAS REPLACED AND SECURED.  THER WAS NO GROUND CONTAMINATION AND AFTER CAR WAS REPAIRED, IT WAS RELEASED.

column168: UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS H.W. RODAGOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS THAT TANK CAR KCCX 2509 WAS LEAKING.  INSPECTION BY MR. RODADOUGH DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A FAILED RUPTURE DISC.  MR. RODABOUGH REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISC AND CLEANED THE CAR.  REPAIRS AND CLEANUP WERE COMPLETE AT 2340 HOURS.

column168: TRAIL LRH50-16 (EL DORADO TURN) DERAILED EAST OF CHIDESTER, ARKANSAS, DERAILING EIGHT CARS, TWO BEING AMMONIUM NITRATE FERTILIZER (BKTY 1110 AND MP 717198) WHICH SPILLED DUE TO FALLING ON SIDES ALLOWING HATCH COVERS TO OPEN.  CARS WERE RE-RAILED, HATCH COVERS CLOSED, SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PICKED UP AND DISPOSED IN LAND FILL.  SHIPPER WAS ON SCENE AND ALL REPORTING AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED. NOTE: REFERENCE EDCX 6025 REPORT ON NITRIC ACID/DERAILMENT.  ATTACHED 5800.1 WERE ALL INVOLVED IN SAME DERAILMENT 09/17/90 IN CHIDESTER, ARKANSAS.  MP 717198, UP 73014, BKTY 1110 AND PLCX 19131.

column168: ON 09/04/90, YARDMASTER GERRY MARTIN REPORTED A SLIGHT ODOR AROUND TANK CAR GATX 92635.  SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) CARL ZERWECK RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED A SLIGHT ODOR OF AMMONIA UPON LIFTING THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  THE ORIGIN OF THE ODOR WAS A LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE.  SSA/HM ZERWECK TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND NUT AND THE ODOR WAS ELIMINATED.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.
